<span id="freeTextContainer17996012342533640079">Actually 4.5 stars....<br/><br/>Finally the book is out. For past one year we (and here I can talk about four of us) have been waiting for the release of this book. Checking every month and then on a weekly basis. Its one of the firsts in Mythological fiction in India based on God Shiva. For me Shiva is probably the most maverick of the Trimurti of Gods – Brahma, Vishnu &amp; Mahesh – birth, life &amp; death and comes across as someone so un-God like. He is not saintly or perfect, he does not follow rules, his an</span>
  <span id="freeText17996012342533640079" style="display:none">Actually 4.5 stars....<br /><br />Finally the book is out. For past one year we (and here I can talk about four of us) have been waiting for the release of this book. Checking every month and then on a weekly basis. Its one of the firsts in Mythological fiction in India based on God Shiva. For me Shiva is probably the most maverick of the Trimurti of Gods – Brahma, Vishnu &amp; Mahesh – birth, life &amp; death and comes across as someone so un-God like. He is not saintly or perfect, he does not follow rules, his anger is earth shaking, his lifestyle is bohemian, he follows his emotions, and he loves or hates to the extremes. Unlike Vishnu the charmer &amp; his aura and Brahma with his multiple heads and books, Shiva represents the God of the free spirits, who do not believe in right or wrong but believe in him and only him. He smokes a pot, and enjoys his bhang, plays with snakes and drinks his poison. <br /><br />To read more:<br /><a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://storywala.blogspot.in/2011/11/secret-of-nagas-trilogy-continues.html">http://storywala.blogspot.in/2011/11/...</a></span>
  <a data-text-id="17996012342533640079" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
