        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer292619338" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11021028535807730964">the book is dissapointing to say the least,,, the author is in too hurry to declare his character as great,, there plans as marvellous and there actions as something of legendary,, what he lacks is writing,, either he believes that reader to too busy to read the character buildup, or he believes reader would be idiot enough to accept any structure to be divine just because author say it so...<br/><br/>means what is point of writing it if u not bother to describe it to the full details,,, one of the main s</span>
  <span id="freeText11021028535807730964" style="display:none">the book is dissapointing to say the least,,, the author is in too hurry to declare his character as great,, there plans as marvellous and there actions as something of legendary,, what he lacks is writing,, either he believes that reader to too busy to read the character buildup, or he believes reader would be idiot enough to accept any structure to be divine just because author say it so...<br /><br />means what is point of writing it if u not bother to describe it to the full details,,, one of the main strong point of fantasy + Fiction + Myth is the amount of details that r provided (while still leaving a lot to imagination),,, author simply lacks that,,, he seems to be in a hurry to finish the book...<br /><br />people who r used to LOTR or other big fantasy fiction series (specially those who want there character to be developed in front of them and r not afraid of going through so called voluminous will be highly dissapointed by this book). the book is good for the people who wants to boast that they have read a triology/fantasy/fiction saga. <br /><br />in my honest opinion this whole TRIOLOGY could have been summed in one book easily, given the kind of haste author shows in finishing a scene/sequence,,, and the amount that hes writing I m sure he will come up with next part ASAP as he might wanna cash on the sort of buzz that the book has created...<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="11021028535807730964" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

